{"key":"post-17083679","value":"<?xml version=\"1.0\"?>\n<post>\n<id>17083679</id>\n<content>&lt;/font&gt;&lt;blockquote&gt;&lt;font class=&quot;small&quot;&gt;Quote:&lt;/font&gt;&lt;hr /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;a 24 soak is all the moisture they can take without bursting, in that case, skip the simmer. &lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;hr /&gt;&lt;/blockquote&gt;&lt;font class=&quot;post&quot;&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;Incorrect info.&amp;nbsp; Rye grains don't burst from soaking; it softens and hydrates them.&amp;nbsp; The boil doesn't cause hydrated grains to burst, because they're already softened.&amp;nbsp; The boil is not to hydrate the grains.&amp;nbsp; The boil is to get the grains hot so the excess moisture steams off after draining.&amp;nbsp; It's all demonstrated in the &lt;a href=&quot;http://www.mushroomvideos.com/Grain-Preparation&quot; target=&quot;_blank&quot; rel=&quot;nofollow noreferrer noopener&quot;&gt;rye grain prep video&lt;/a&gt; that has been successfully used by tens of thousands of growers who &lt;i&gt;follow the video without making modifications to the procedure.&lt;/i&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;To flexorman, gypsum will appear to dissolve in water.&amp;nbsp; It's still there.&amp;nbsp; Most horticultural grade gypsum in the US is made from drywall scraps.&amp;nbsp; I have no idea how drywall is made in your country, but if you're not using the green board gypsum intended for bathrooms, it won't have fungicides in it.&lt;br /&gt;RR</content>\n<name>RogerRabbit</name>\n<next>17083736</next>\n<prev>17083564</prev>\n<first>17083242</first>\n<last>17153398</last>\n<when>1350993257</when>\n<utime>10/23/12 02:54 PM</utime>\n</post>"}